1) State is just a way to store data inside a component â€” like a variable that can change and automatically update the UI when it does.

`
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);


 `count` â†’ your current value (like a variable)
 `setCount` â†’ a function to change the value
 `useState(0)` â†’ sets the initial value


 ğŸ” Why do we use State?

Imagine a counter app:


<button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Click Me</button>


Every time you click, React:

1. Changes the value
2. Re-renders the UI with the **new value**

So:
ğŸ–±ï¸ You click â†’ ğŸ§  State changes â†’ ğŸ–¼ï¸ UI updates automatically



 âœ… When to use State (and which one to use)

| Situation                            | Should I use `useState`? | Example value stored                |
| ------------------------------------ | ------------------------ | ----------------------------------- |
| User input (text, email, etc.)       | âœ… Yes                    | `name`, `email`, `password`         |
| Button clicks / toggles              | âœ… Yes                    | `isVisible`, `isDarkMode`, `count`  |
| Conditional display (like error msg) | âœ… Yes                    | `errorShown`, `formSubmitted`       |
| Data from backend (once fetched)     | âœ… Yes (initially empty)  | `products`, `userProfile`, `posts`  |
| Fixed data that never changes        | âŒ No (use `const`)       | API key, heading text, static links |



ğŸ’¡ Remember:

 `useState` is for changing data
 When state changes, the component re-renders
You can have **many `useState` in one component



 ğŸ§ª Real Example: Login Form


const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
const [password, setPassword] = useState('');
const [submitted, setSubmitted] = useState(false);
const [error, setError] = useState('');


âš ï¸ Don't use state when:

 The data will **never change**
 It's calculated on the fly from props

2)Strict mode

 -->build in component

there are two ways to use Strict mode

  1)in index.jsx
     
    <React.StrictMode>
    <App />
   </React.StrictMode>

 -->we just need to import React from'react';


   2)

    <StrictMode>
    <App />
    </StrictMode>

    -->but we need to import {StrictMode} from 'react';
       and also need to use wrapping component like 
       <StrictMode>
       </StrictMode>

strictmode is used to excute every component function twice

All of these checks are development-only and do not impact the production build.


3) creating new array for old array OR Updating the array or object

function(prev) {
  return [...prev, newItem];
}

example:

   function addTodo(task) {
  setTodos((prev) => [
    ...prev,
    { id: Date.now(), task, completed: false }
  ]);
}

4) Return

   When you use return inside a function, it immediately stops the function from running further.

   if (!input.trim()) return;

